</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#12350C">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
I know a lot of us chose to play a sorceror primarily because of the crowd control spells we have.  If you came from EQ, you knew how essential it was to have a good enchanter in your group.  I have been playing a sorc since the day DAoC was released and I'm currently level 29.  I have come to a couple of conclusions that has changed my entire outlook on the class.   These conclusions are based on the following factors:<P>1)  I always try to group.  Soloing is boring and not efficient if you want to maximize EXP gain.  The ONLY time I will ever solo is if I can't find a group.<P>2)  I almost always end up joining pickup groups.  I usually play late at night so most of my guildmates have already logged off for the evening.<BR> <BR>3)  Sorcerors and pickup groups do not mix well.  Because there aren't that many sorcs out there, most groups have no idea how to group with us.  I joined a high 20/low 30 group (8 members) in the Catacombs last night.  I had to instruct two of the members how the /assist feature worked and how to create a macro key for it.  Even then, people continually broke mez on almost every pull.  The bottom line is that the majority of the time I find myself in groups that, because they can't adapt their playstyle, prevent me from being fully effective as a crowd controller.<BR>  <BR>4)  Based on #3, if I continue to focus on putting most of my spec points into Mind, then I think I will end up gimping myself in the PvE game.  Sure I could get a better AE mez if I continued to put points into Mind.  But does it really make a difference that your AE mez has a longer duration when the majority of the time someone breaks it early?  The way I see it right now, the highest I think I will raise Mind is 25.  That gives me a 46 second AE mez and a 82 ot STR/CON debuff.  These spells should be good enough for me to be effective at crowd controlling and debuffing in both RvR and PvE.  If spec levels have an impact on resist rates, then I will just get +Mind items to boost my skill up to 2/3 my level.  I miss out on being able to charm a level 41-50 pet, but I never use my pet in full groups anyway.  <P>Instead of focusing on Mind, instead I will put my spec points into either Body or Matter.  If the new Matter spells are focused on RvR, and since thats the main focus of the high level game, that may end up being the smartest move if you want to be effective in RvR.  Until these new Matter spells get added, I won't be spending any spec points when I level.  Right now I have over 80 spec points saved up.  By the time the new Matter spells get added, I should be able to raise it to around level 15 or so, assuming the new spell lines are worth it.  If the new Matter spells are not that great, then I can focus on raising Body.  This gives me more nuking power plus will give me an AE root, which in some situations may be better than AE mez.<P>5)  With all the whining/complaining going on the IGN Dev board about AE mezzing/stunning in RvR, I think that there is a possibility that AE mezzing in RvR may get nerfed sometime in the future.  Whether this nerf would be justified or not is not the issue.  If you believe that the squeaky wheel always gets the grease, then its a safe assumption that Mythic will nerf AE mezzing for all three realms in order to satisfy the masses, whether it is justified or not.  I personally hope they don't change how AE mez works, and instead give Albion and Hibernia a counter to the Midgard AE stun.  But assuming the worst case scenario that AE mezzing in RvR gets nerfed, then sorcs who focus on Mind will get screwed.    <P>To sum it all up,  when I started playing, I thought focusing on Mind was the smart move in order to be an effective sorceror in the high level game.  Now, I'm inclined to believe, based on the factors I listed above, that spreading out spec points to where I'm at least 1/2 in all three paths is probably the smartest and safest choice in order to remain effective in the high level game.<P>Galtin
</FONT>
